ate=2007|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9789004156050|p=158}}\n</ref>\n* [[760]] &ndash; Fourteenth recorded perihelion passage of [[Halley's Comet]].\n* [[853]] &ndash; A Byzantine fleet [[Sack of Damietta (853)|sacks and destroys]] undefended [[Damietta]] in [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Venning|first=Timothy|title=A Chronology of the Byzantine Empire|location=Basingstoke, UK|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|date=2006|isbn=9780230505865|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NjVaCwAAQBAJ|page=257}}</ref>\n*[[1176]] &ndash; The Hashshashin ([[Order of Assassins|Assassins]]) attempt to assassinate [[Saladin]] near [[Aleppo]].\n*[[1200]] &ndash; King [[John, King of England|John of England]] and King [[Philip II of France]] sign the [[Treaty of Le Goulet]].\n*[[1246]] &ndash; [[Henry Raspe, Landgrave of Thuringia|Henry Raspe]] is elected [[anti-king]] of the [[Kingdom of Germany]] in opposition to [[Conrad IV of Germany|Conrad IV]].\n*[[1254]] &ndash; [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Serbian King]] [[Stefan Uro\u0161 I]] and the [[Republic of Venice]] sign a peace treaty.\n*[[1370]] &ndash; [[Brussels massacre]]: Hundreds Jews are murdered and the rest of the Jewish community is banished from [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]], for allegedly descrating consecrated [[Sacramental bread|Host]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jacob|first=Heinrich Eduard|title=Six Thousand Years of Bread: Its Holy and Unholy History|location=New York|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|date=2007|isbn=9781602391246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTO1aUu14sAC|pages=168\u2013170}}</ref>\n*[[1377]] &ndash; [[Pope Gregory XI]] issues five [[papal bull]]s to denounce the [[doctrine]]s of English [[theology|theologian]] [[John Wycliffe]].\n*[[1455]] &ndash; Start of the [[Wars of the Roses]]: At the [[First Battle of St Albans]], [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, Duke of York]], defeats and captures King [[Henry VI of England]].\n*[[1520]] &ndash; The [[Massacre in the Great Temple of Tenochtitlan|massacre at the festival of T\u00f3xcatl]] takes place during the [[Fall of Tenochtitlan]], resulting in turning the Aztecs against the Spanish.<ref>Revista de la Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de M\u00e9xico, UNAM Volume 49, Issues 522-527 p 40</ref>\n*[[1629]] &ndash; [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Ferdinand II, Holy Roman Emperor|Ferdinand II]] and [[List of Danish monarchs|Danish King]] [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]] sign the [[Treaty of L\u00fcbeck]] ending Danish intervention in the [[Thirty Years' War]].\n*[[1762]] &ndash; Sweden and [[Prussia]] sign the [[Treaty of Hamburg (1762)|Treaty of Hamburg]].\n*  1762   &ndash; [[Trevi Fountain]] is officially completed and inaugurated in Rome.<ref>{{cite book|last=Carlson|first=Victor|title=Hubert Robert: Drawings and Watercolors|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=National Gallery of Art|date=1978|oclc=299971200|page=9|postscript=none}}; {{cite book|last1=d'Onofrio|first1=Cesare|last2=Dellacher|first2=Max|title=Le fontane di Roma: con documenti e disegni inediti|location=Rome|publisher=Staderini Editioni|date=1957|oclc=249113666|page=viii|postscript=none}}; {{cite journal|last=Cooke|first=H. L.|title=The Documents Relating to the Fountain of Trevi|journal=Art Bulletin|volume=38|issue=3|date=1956|pages=149\u2013173 at 168|doi=10.1080/00043079.1956.11408329}}</ref>\n*[[1766]] &ndash; A [[1766 Istanbul earthquake|large earthquake]] causes heavy damage and loss of life in [[Istanbul]] and the Marmara region.<ref name=\"Ambraseys2000\">{{Cite journal|url=https://academic.oup.com/gji/article/141/3/F1/613019|title=Seismicity of the Sea of Marmara (Turkey) since 1500|author1=N. N. Ambraseys|authorlink=Nicholas Ambraseys|author2=J. A. Jackson|language=en|journal=Geophysical Journal International|volume=141|issue=3|pages=F1|date=June 2000|bibcode=2000GeoJI.141F...1A|access-date=7 November 2019|doi=10.1046/j.1365-246x.2000.00137.x}}</ref>\n*[[1804]] &ndash; The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] officially begins as the [[Corps of Discovery]] departs from St. Charles, Missouri.\n*[[1807]] &ndash; A [[grand jury]] indicts former [[Vice President of the United States]] [[Aaron Burr]] on a charge of [[treason]].\n*[[1809]] &ndash; On the second and last day of the [[Battle of Aspern-Essling]] (near [[Vienna]], Austria), [[Napoleon]] I is repelled by an enemy army for the first time.\n*[[1816]] &ndash; A mob in [[Littleport, Cambridgeshire]], England, [[Ely and Littleport riots of 1816|riots]] concerning high unemployment and rising grain costs spreads to [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] the next day.\n*[[1819]] &ndash; {{SS|Savannah}} leaves port at [[Savannah, Georgia]], United States, on a voyage to become the first [[steamship]] to cross the Atlantic Ocean.\n*[[1826]] &ndash; {{HMS|Beagle}} departs on its first voyage.\n*[[1840]] &ndash; The [[penal transportation]] of British [[convict]]s to the [[New South Wales]] [[colony]] is abolished.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; [[History of Martinique#1815\u20131899|Slavery is abolished]] in [[Martinique]].\n*[[1849]] &ndash; Future [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] is issued a [[patent]] for an [[Abraham Lincoln's patent|invention to lift boats]], making him the only U.S. President to ever hold a patent.\n*[[1856]] &ndash; [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] [[Preston Brooks]] of [[South Carolina]] severely beats [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Charles Sumner]] of [[Massachusetts]] with a cane in the hall of the [[United States Senate]] for a speech Sumner had made regarding  [[Southern United States|Southerners]] and [[slavery in the United States|slavery]].\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces begin the [[Siege of Port Hudson]] which lasts 48 days, the longest siege in U.S. military history.\n*[[1864]] &ndash; American Civil War: After ten weeks, the [[Union Army]]'s [[Red River Campaign]] ends in failure.\n*[[1872]] &ndash; [[Reconstruction Era]]: President [[Ulysses S. Grant]] signs the [[Amnesty Act]] into law, restoring full [[civil and political rights]] to all but about 500 Confederate sympathizers.\n*[[1900]] &ndash; The [[Associated Press]] is formed in [[New York City]] as a non-profit news cooperative.\n*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[Wright brothers]] are granted U.S. patent number 821,393 for their \"[[Airplane|Flying-Machine]]\".\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Lassen Peak]] erupts with a powerful force, the only volcano besides [[Mount St. Helens]] to erupt in the contiguous U.S. during the 20th century.\n*  1915   &ndash; Three trains collide in the [[Quintinshill rail disaster]] near [[Gretna Green]], Scotland, killing 227 people and injuring 246.\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Chiang Kai-shek]] replaces the communists in [[Kuomintang]] China.\n*[[1927]] &ndash; Near [[Xining]], China, an 8.3 magnitude [[1927 Gulang earthquake|earthquake]] causes 200,000 deaths in one of the world's most destructive earthquakes.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; World War II: Germany and Italy sign the [[Pact of Steel]].\n*[[1941]] &ndash; During the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]], British troops take [[Fallujah]].\n*[[1942]] &ndash; Mexico enters World War II, joining the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]].\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Joseph Stalin]] disbands the [[Comintern]].\n*[[1947]] &ndash; [[Cold War]]: The [[Truman Doctrine]] goes into effect, aiding Turkey & Greece.\n*[[1957]] &ndash; South Africa's government approves of [[apartheid|racial separation]] in universities.\n*[[1958]] &ndash; The [[1958 riots in Ceylon]] become a watershed in the race relations of various ethnic communities of Sri Lanka. The total deaths is estimated at 300, mostly [[Tamils]].\n*[[1960]] &ndash; The [[1960 Valdivia earthquake|Great Chilean earthquake]], measuring 9.5 on the [[moment magnitude scale]], hits southern [[Chile]], becoming the most powerful earthquake ever recorded.\n*[[1962]] &ndash; [[Continental Airlines Flight 11]] crashes after bombs explode on board.\n*[[1963]] &ndash; Greek left-wing politician [[Grigoris Lambrakis]] is shot in an assassination attempt, and dies five days later.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] launches the [[Great Society]].\n*[[1967]] &ndash; Egypt closes the [[Straits of Tiran]] to Israeli shipping.\n*  1967   &ndash; [[L'Innovation Department Store fire|L'Innovation]] department store in [[Brussels]], Belgium, burns down, resulting in 323 dead or missing and 150 injured, the most devastating fire in Belgian history.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; The nuclear-powered [[submarine]] {{USS|Scorpion|SSN-589|6}} sinks with 99 men aboard, 400 miles southwest of the [[Azores]].\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Apollo 10]]'s lunar module flies within {{convert|8.4|nmi|km|lk=in|0}} of the [[moon]]'s surface.\n*[[1972]] &ndash; Ceylon adopts a [[Sri Lankan Constitution of 1972|new constitution]], becoming a [[republic]] and changing its name to [[Sri Lanka]], and joins the [[Commonwealth of Nations]].\n*  1972   &ndash; Over 400 women in [[Derry]], [[Northern Ireland]] attack the offices of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] following the shooting by the [[Irish Republican Army]] of a young British soldier on leave.\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Hashimpura massacre]] occurs in [[Meerut]], India.\n*  1987   &ndash;  First ever [[1987 Rugby World Cup|Rugby World Cup]] kicks off with [[New Zealand Rugby Union|New Zealand]] playing [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] at [[Eden Park]] in [[Auckland]], New Zealand.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Yemen Arab Republic|North]] and [[South Yemen]] are [[Yemeni unification|unified]] to create the Republic of [[Yemen]].\n*[[1992]] &ndash; [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Croatia]] and [[Slovenia]] join the [[United Nations]].\n*[[1994]] &ndash; A worldwide trade embargo against [[Haiti]] goes into effect to punish its military rulers for not reinstating the country's ousted elected leader, [[Jean-Bertrand Aristide]].\n*[[1996]] &ndash; The Burmese military regime jails 71 supporters of [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] in a bid to block a pro-democracy meeting.\n*[[1998]] &ndash; A U.S. federal judge rules that [[United States Secret Service|U.S. Secret Service]] agents can be compelled to testify before a [[grand jury]] concerning the [[Lewinsky scandal]] involving President [[Bill Clinton]].\n*[[2000]] &ndash; In [[Sri Lanka]], over 150 [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Tamil]] rebels are killed over two days of fighting for control in [[Jaffna]]. \n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[Civil rights movement]]: A jury in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], convicts former [[Ku Klux Klan]] member [[Bobby Frank Cherry]] of the [[1963]] murder of four girls in the [[16th Street Baptist Church bombing]].\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Air India Express Flight 812|Air India Express]] [[Boeing 737]] crashes over a cliff upon landing at [[Mangalore]], India, killing 158 of 166 people on board, becoming the deadliest crash involving a Boeing 737.\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Inter Milan]] beat [[Bayern Munich]] 2-0 in the [[Uefa Champions League]] final in [[Madrid]], [[Spain]] to become the first, and so far only, Italian team to win the historic treble (Serie A, Coppa Italia, Champions League). \n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[2011 Joplin tornado|An EF5 tornado]] strikes [[Joplin, Missouri]], killing 158 people and wreaking $2.8 billion in damages, the costliest and seventh-deadliest single tornado in U.S. history.\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Tokyo Skytree]] opens to the public. It is the [[List of tallest towers|tallest tower in the world]] (634 m), and the second tallest man-made structure on Earth after [[Burj Khalifa]] (829.8 m).\n*[[2014]] &ndash; General [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]] becomes interim leader of Thailand in a military [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]], following six months of political turmoil.\n*  2014   &ndash; An [[May 2014 \u00dcr\u00fcmqi attack|explosion]] occurs in [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi]], capital of China's far-western [[Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region|Xinjiang]] region, resulting in at least 43 deaths and 91 injuries.\n*[[2015]] &ndash; The [[Republic of Ireland]] becomes the first nation in the world to [[2015 Irish constitutional referendums|legalize gay marriage]] in a public referendum.\n*[[2017]] &ndash; Twenty-two people are killed at an [[Ariana Grande]] concert in the [[Manchester Arena bombing|2017 Manchester Arena bombing]].\n*[[2017]] &ndash; United States [[President Donald Trump]] visits the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre]] in [[Jerusalem]] and becomes the first sitting U.S. President to visit the [[Western Wall]].\n<!--Please DO NOT add video games, video game consoles, concerts, movie, TV or album releases, as they WILL be deleted-->\n\n==Births==\n* [[626]] &ndash; [[Itzam K'an Ahk I]], Mayan king (d. 686)\n*[[1009]] &ndash; [[Su Xun]], Chinese writer (d. 1066)\n*[[1408]] &ndash; [[Annamacharya]], Hindu saint (d. 1503)\n*[[1539]] &ndash; [[Edward Seymour, 1st Earl of Hertford]] (d. 1621)\n*[[1622]] &ndash; [[Louis de Buade de Frontenac]], French soldier and governor (d. 1698)\n*[[1644]] &ndash; [[Gabri\u00ebl Grupello]], Flemish Baroque sculptor (d. 1730)\n*[[1650]] &ndash; [[Richard Brakenburgh]], Dutch Golden Age painter (d. 1702)\n*[[1694]] &ndash; [[Daniel Gran]], Austrian painter (d. 1757)\n*[[1715]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois-Joachim de Pierre de Bernis]], French cardinal and diplomat (d. 1794)\n*[[1733]] &ndash; [[Hubert Robert]], French painter (d. 1808)\n*[[1752]] &ndash; [[Louis Legendre]], French butcher and politician (d. 1797)\n*[[1762]] &ndash; [[Henry Bathurst, 3rd Earl Bathurst]], English politician (d. 1834)\n*[[1770]] &ndash; [[Princess Elizabeth of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1840)\n*[[1772]] &ndash; [[Ram Mohan Roy]], Indian philosopher and reformer (d. 1833)\n*[[1782]] &ndash; [[Hirose Tans\u014d]], Japanese neo-Confucian scholar, teacher, writer (d. 1856)\n*[[1783]] &ndash; [[William Sturgeon]], English physicist and inventor, invented the [[electromagnet]] and [[electric motor]] (d. 1850)\n*[[1808]] &ndash; [[G\u00e9rard de Nerval]], French poet and translator (d. 1855)\n*[[1811]] &ndash; [[Giulia Grisi]], Italian soprano (d. 1869)\n*  1811   &ndash; [[Henry Pelham-Clinton, 5th Duke of Newcastle]], English politician (d. 1864)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[Richard Wagner]], German composer (d. 1883)\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Amalia Lindegren]], Swedish painter (d. 1891)\n*[[1820]] &ndash; [[Worthington Whittredge]], American painter (d. 1910)\n*[[1828]] &ndash; [[Albrecht von Graefe]], German ophthalmologist and academic (d. 1870)\n*[[1831]] &ndash; [[Henry Vandyke Carter]], English anatomist and surgeon (d. 1897)\n*[[1833]] &ndash; [[F\u00e9lix Bracquemond]], French painter and etcher (d. 1914)\n*  1833   &ndash; [[Manuel Ruiz Zorrilla]], Spanish politician; served as [[Prime Minister of Spain]] from 1871-73 (d. 1895)\n*[[1841]] &ndash; [[Catulle Mend\u00e8s]], French poet, author, and playwright (d. 1909)\n*[[1844]] &ndash; [[Mary Cassatt]], American painter and educator (d. 1926)\n*[[1846]] &ndash; [[Rita Cetina Guti\u00e9rrez]], Mexican poet, educator, and activist (d. 1908)\n*[[1848]] &ndash; [[Fritz von Uhde]], German painter and educator (d. 1911)\n*[[1849]] &ndash; [[Aston Webb]], English architect and academic (d. 1930)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[\u00c9mile Sauret]], French violinist and composer (d. 1920)\n*[[1858]] &ndash; [[Belmiro de Almeida]], Brazilian painter, illustrator, sculptor (d. 1935)\n*[[1859]] &ndash; [[Arthur Conan Doyle]], British writer (d. 1930)\n*  1859   &ndash; [[Tsubouchi Sh\u014dy\u014d]], Japanese author, playwright, and educator (d. 1935)\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[Willy St\u00f6wer]], German author and illustrator (d. 1931)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Augusto Pestana (politician)|Augusto Pestana]], Brazilian engineer and politician (d. 1934)\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[Daniel Fran\u00e7ois Malan]], South African clergyman and politician, 5th [[Prime Minister of South Africa]] (d. 1959)\n*[[1876]] &ndash; [[Julius Klinger]], Austrian painter and illustrator (d. 1942)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[Warwick Armstrong]], Australian cricketer and journalist (d. 1947)\n*  1879   &ndash; [[Jean Cras]], French admiral and composer (d. 1932)\n*  1879   &ndash; [[Symon Petliura]], Ukrainian statesman and independence leader (d. 1926)\n*[[1880]] &ndash; [[Francis de Miomandre]], French author and translator (d. 1959)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Giacomo Matteotti]], Italian lawyer and politician (d. 1924)\n*  1885   &ndash; [[Soemu Toyoda]], Japanese admiral (d. 1957)\n*  1887   &ndash; [[A. W. Sandberg]], Danish film director and screenwriter (d. 1938)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Johannes R. Becher]], German politician, novelist, and poet (d. 1958)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Friedrich Pollock]], German sociologist and philosopher (d. 1970)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Robert Neumann (writer)|Robert Neumann]], German and English-speaking author (d. 1975)\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Juan Arvizu]], Mexican lyric opera tenor and bolero vocalist (d.1985)\n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Maurice J. Tobin]], American politician, 6th [[United States Secretary of Labor]] (d. 1953)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Al Simmons]], American baseball player and coach (d. 1956)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[Uno Lamm]], Swedish electrical engineer and inventor (d. 1989)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Bodo von Borries]], German physicist and academic, co-invented the [[electron microscope]] (d. 1956)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Tom Driberg]], British politician (d. 1976)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Herg\u00e9]], Belgian author and illustrator (d. 1983)\n*  1907   &ndash; [[Laurence Olivier]], English actor, director, and producer (d. 1989)\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[Horton Smith]], American golfer and captain (d. 1963)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Margaret Mee]], English illustrator and educator (d. 1988)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Herbert C. Brown]], English-American chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2004)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Rafael Gil]], Spanish director and screenwriter (d. 1986)\n*  1913   &ndash; [[Dominique Rolin]], Belgian author (d. 2012)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Max Kohnstamm]], Dutch historian 